1
00:01:17,833 --> 00:01:20,065
I've lived in the
theatre since I was a kid.

2
00:01:20,266 --> 00:01:21,965
what I don't know about acting

3
00:01:22,166 --> 00:01:22,766
isn't worth knowing.

4
00:01:22,966 --> 00:01:25,299
now, you may be 20 years
old and just beginning,

5
00:01:26,166 --> 00:01:28,033
but I think you're a genius.

6
00:01:28,433 --> 00:01:30,900
you've got magnetism,
but no idea how to use it.

7
00:01:31,299 --> 00:01:33,566
you have to grab the audience
by the throat and say:

8
00:01:34,166 --> 00:01:36,299
"now, you buggers, you
pay attention to me!"

9
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:41,033
and remember this,

10
00:01:41,533 --> 00:01:43,466
when you're on the stage acting,

11
00:01:44,266 --> 00:01:46,000
theatre is the only reality.

12
00:01:48,466 --> 00:01:49,765
everything else, the world outside,

13
00:01:49,966 --> 00:01:52,233
what civilians call the real world,

14
00:01:53,266 --> 00:01:54,499
is nothing but fantasy.

15
00:01:54,700 --> 00:01:56,933
and I bloody well
won't let you forget it.

16
00:01:58,733 --> 00:02:01,099
the trouble is, darling,
I'm an incurable romantic.

17
00:02:05,366 --> 00:02:06,933
I believe in love,

18
00:02:08,033 --> 00:02:09,699
I believe in happiness,

19
00:02:10,733 --> 00:02:11,333
I believe in us.

20
00:02:11,333 --> 00:02:14,033
(Archie) no, you don't.
you're just saying that.

21
00:02:16,166 --> 00:02:18,266
there's someone else, isn't there?

22
00:02:19,199 --> 00:02:20,766
I love you, I do.

23
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:24,066
I do, I
love you--

24
00:02:24,433 --> 00:02:25,465
and I used to believe

25
00:02:25,666 --> 00:02:27,433
we'd live happily ever after.

26
00:02:29,033 --> 00:02:30,032
didn't you?

27
00:02:30,233 --> 00:02:32,099
with every fiber of my being.

28
00:02:34,166 --> 00:02:35,633
only now...

29
00:02:36,566 --> 00:02:38,199
[audience applauding]

30
00:03:21,366 --> 00:03:22,866
[car honking]

31
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:25,199
[clock bell tolls]

32
00:03:26,466 --> 00:03:27,398
[door squeaking]

33
00:03:27,599 --> 00:03:29,432
good morning, miss Lambert.

34
00:03:29,633 --> 00:03:30,233
good morning, Margery,

35
00:03:30,366 --> 00:03:32,599
is anyone with my lord and master?

36
00:03:33,233 --> 00:03:34,866
(Margery) no.

37
00:03:35,966 --> 00:03:38,066
darling, what are you doing here?

38
00:03:38,733 --> 00:03:39,799
I want an answer, Michael.

39
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:41,465
what's the question?

40
00:03:41,666 --> 00:03:42,266
what did I say to you

41
00:03:42,466 --> 00:03:44,533
before we went to sleep last night, hmm?

42
00:03:48,599 --> 00:03:50,199
uh, I give up. what did you say to me

43
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:52,065
before we went to sleep last night?

44
00:03:52,266 --> 00:03:53,165
I said I was tired.

45
00:03:53,366 --> 00:03:55,766
it seems a perfectly natural thing
to say before you go to sleep.

46
00:03:56,133 --> 00:03:58,533
Christ, Michael, you can be
an irritating little shit!

47
00:03:59,066 --> 00:04:00,766
Julia, Julia, really,

48
00:04:01,033 --> 00:04:03,199
if your public could
only hear your language.

49
00:04:03,566 --> 00:04:04,432
I want them to hear.

50
00:04:04,633 --> 00:04:06,365
I want every bloody one of them to hear.

51
00:04:06,566 --> 00:04:08,400
I'm tired. I am utterly exhausted.

52
00:04:08,666 --> 00:04:10,299
I need a holiday.

53
00:04:10,866 --> 00:04:11,799
just admit it, Michael.

54
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,033
you've never understood what it means

55
00:04:14,433 --> 00:04:15,398
to carry a play,

56
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:16,465
to sweat it out night after night.

57
00:04:16,666 --> 00:04:19,266
I'm the only one who takes it
seriously, Michael, you know that.

58
00:04:19,766 --> 00:04:22,366
all you do is count the money and
think it's a bloody great lark.

59
00:04:23,666 --> 00:04:24,599
take the play off.

60
00:04:24,800 --> 00:04:26,566
but we'll lose a fortune.

61
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:28,765
our partner won't like it.

62
00:04:28,966 --> 00:04:30,699
to hell with dolly!

63
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:36,732
[sighing]

64
00:04:36,933 --> 00:04:38,432
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

65
00:04:38,633 --> 00:04:40,566
god, I didn't mean to be so vile.

66
00:04:40,800 --> 00:04:42,899
it's just I'm-- I'm
near to breaking point.

67
00:04:44,933 --> 00:04:46,733
everything's so tedious.

68
00:04:47,433 --> 00:04:48,632
[sighing]

69
00:04:48,833 --> 00:04:50,566
I want something to happen.

70
00:04:51,300 --> 00:04:52,600
what?

71
00:04:53,033 --> 00:04:54,399
I wish I knew.

72
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:56,899
please. please close the
play at the end of the month.

73
00:05:00,433 --> 00:05:01,033
[exhales]

74
00:05:01,233 --> 00:05:03,032
yeah. I really do
have to think about it.

75
00:05:03,233 --> 00:05:05,300
we can't have the theatre dark.

76
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:07,600
hmm?

77
00:05:07,699 --> 00:05:09,933
I'll try and see what
I can do. I promise.

78
00:05:10,699 --> 00:05:12,033
hmm?

79
00:05:12,233 --> 00:05:13,332
please.

80
00:05:13,533 --> 00:05:14,632
I promise.

81
00:05:14,833 --> 00:05:16,266
thank you.

82
00:05:17,366 --> 00:05:18,065
you were very quiet

83
00:05:18,266 --> 00:05:19,698
leaving the house this morning.

84
00:05:19,899 --> 00:05:21,032
well, I didn't want to wake you.

85
00:05:21,233 --> 00:05:22,165
you were dead to the world.

86
00:05:22,366 --> 00:05:24,600
hmm. I did my exercises
and went for a run.

87
00:05:24,966 --> 00:05:26,600
exercises, running...

88
00:05:27,033 --> 00:05:27,633
god, Michael,

89
00:05:27,699 --> 00:05:29,633
you're the vainest man in London.

90
00:05:29,933 --> 00:05:31,466
me, vain? nonsense.

91
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:32,400
[giggles]

92
00:05:32,366 --> 00:05:35,333
I just want to preserve my magnificent
good looks for as long as possible.

93
00:05:36,300 --> 00:05:37,766
[chuckling]

94
00:05:38,766 --> 00:05:39,765
oh, yes, speaking of good looks,

95
00:05:39,966 --> 00:05:42,233
did you notice that
young man as you came in?

96
00:05:42,933 --> 00:05:43,765
no.

97
00:05:43,966 --> 00:05:44,865
he's an American.

98
00:05:45,066 --> 00:05:47,266
son of a friend of a
friend of Eddie Gilbert's.

99
00:05:47,800 --> 00:05:50,033
I can't see what that's
got to do with me.

100
00:05:50,266 --> 00:05:51,965
he admires you tremendously.

101
00:05:52,166 --> 00:05:54,466
oh, he sounds frightfully intelligent.

102
00:05:55,266 --> 00:05:56,733
what's his name?

103
00:05:57,199 --> 00:05:58,733
can't remember.

104
00:05:58,933 --> 00:05:59,865
uh, unfortunately,

105
00:06:00,066 --> 00:06:01,765
he's as poor as a church mouse.

106
00:06:01,966 --> 00:06:04,233
I thought we might give
him a spot of lunch.

107
00:06:04,666 --> 00:06:07,033
well, he's awfully
good-mannered, for an American.

108
00:06:08,166 --> 00:06:09,633
(Julia) uh!

109
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:12,832
rubbish mail, Margery.

110
00:06:13,033 --> 00:06:13,633
yes, Mr. Gosselyn.

111
00:06:13,666 --> 00:06:15,966
uh, I would like to
introduce you to my wife,

112
00:06:16,433 --> 00:06:17,033
Julia Lambert.

113
00:06:17,133 --> 00:06:18,565
Julia, this
is-- this is--

114
00:06:18,766 --> 00:06:21,199
this is the young man
I was telling you about.

115
00:06:21,466 --> 00:06:22,399
he wants to learn the business,

116
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,765
so we're starting him
off with our accountant.

117
00:06:24,966 --> 00:06:27,066
it-it's an honor to
meet you, miss Lambert.

118
00:06:27,366 --> 00:06:28,832
I wonder if we could persuade you

119
00:06:29,033 --> 00:06:30,833
to come and eat a chop with us.

120
00:06:31,033 --> 00:06:33,100
Michael will drive you back after lunch.

121
00:06:34,266 --> 00:06:35,698
gee, that's real kind of you.

122
00:06:35,899 --> 00:06:38,033
you two take the lift,
I'll take the stairs.

123
00:06:38,566 --> 00:06:40,166
last one down's a sissy.

124
00:06:40,699 --> 00:06:42,199
miss Lambert,

125
00:06:44,300 --> 00:06:45,632
could I-- could
I ask you a favor?

126
00:06:45,833 --> 00:06:48,666
I can't give you any more
room, if that's what you mean.

127
00:06:49,066 --> 00:06:51,066
no, no, no, it's, uh... I wonder...

128
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:52,400
would you...

129
00:06:52,433 --> 00:06:54,399
would you let me have a photograph?

130
00:06:54,633 --> 00:06:55,299
of course.

131
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:56,299
gee, that's swell of you.

132
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:58,699
I've seen you in
farewell, my love 3 times.

133
00:06:59,033 --> 00:07:00,865
you haven't. have you really?

134
00:07:01,066 --> 00:07:02,232
it's such a silly play.

135
00:07:02,433 --> 00:07:03,132
oh, it's not the play,

136
00:07:03,333 --> 00:07:05,333
it's you. you're just... just great.

137
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:07,732
I'm glad you liked me.

138
00:07:07,933 --> 00:07:09,132
liked you? I loved you.

139
00:07:09,333 --> 00:07:10,498
[elevator thudding]

140
00:07:10,699 --> 00:07:11,299
[door squeaking]

141
00:07:11,466 --> 00:07:12,998
I won. (Julia) what?

142
00:07:13,199 --> 00:07:14,766
well done.

143
00:07:15,433 --> 00:07:17,166
come on, Mr... uh...

144
00:07:40,766 --> 00:07:42,666
all an actress like Julia needs

145
00:07:43,166 --> 00:07:43,998
is a vehicle.

146
00:07:44,199 --> 00:07:46,198
it's the actors the public go to see,

147
00:07:46,399 --> 00:07:46,999
not the play.

148
00:07:46,966 --> 00:07:49,198
that's true in my case. I'd see
you in anything, miss Lambert.

149
00:07:49,399 --> 00:07:51,699
but you know what I'd
really like to find out?

150
00:07:52,133 --> 00:07:52,932
how did you start?

151
00:07:53,133 --> 00:07:54,232
how did you get to be where you are,

152
00:07:54,433 --> 00:07:55,865
owning a theatre, top of the tree?

153
00:07:56,066 --> 00:07:57,099
clean living and hard work. cigarette?

154
00:07:57,300 --> 00:08:00,300
we owe it all to a rude, foul-mouthed
brute called Jimmie Langton.

155
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:02,732
we were in his repertory
company in Middlesbrough.

156
00:08:02,933 --> 00:08:05,500
he knew all there is to know
about theatre and acting.

157
00:08:05,833 --> 00:08:07,899
that's where I met Michael.
that's how we began.

158
00:08:08,566 --> 00:08:10,132
I was a rotten actor.

159
00:08:10,333 --> 00:08:11,698
yes, but you have presence.

160
00:08:11,899 --> 00:08:14,166
the audience always
gasps when you come on.

161
00:08:14,766 --> 00:08:17,066
it's his dazzling good looks, you see.

162
00:08:17,833 --> 00:08:20,000
gee, this is fascinating. fascinating.

163
00:08:20,733 --> 00:08:21,333
dreadfully jealous of him?

164
00:08:21,533 --> 00:08:22,998
you're very sweet, but
I know perfectly well

165
00:08:23,199 --> 00:08:25,532
that all I can play are
diplomats, lawyers and politicians.

166
00:08:25,733 --> 00:08:27,898
I'm more interested in
the business side. that's--

167
00:08:28,099 --> 00:08:29,365
yes, but you know as well as I do

168
00:08:29,566 --> 00:08:31,332
that we'd be nothing without Jimmie.

169
00:08:31,533 --> 00:08:33,766
I always lay a place
for him at the table.

170
00:08:33,966 --> 00:08:35,132
just in case he turns up.

171
00:08:35,333 --> 00:08:36,399
he's been dead for 15 years.

172
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:38,399
yes, but you never know.

173
00:08:39,233 --> 00:08:40,933
he was a monster.

174
00:08:42,366 --> 00:08:44,366
uh, how do you spell your first name?

175
00:08:46,299 --> 00:08:47,600
t-o-m.

176
00:08:50,366 --> 00:08:51,733
[laughing]

177
00:08:52,899 --> 00:08:54,366
[nib squeaking]

178
00:08:57,266 --> 00:08:58,933
[gramophone playing]

179
00:08:59,899 --> 00:09:01,600
[people clapping]

180
00:09:02,733 --> 00:09:04,233
[car honking]

181
00:09:04,966 --> 00:09:06,566
(dancer) hoy!

182
00:09:06,899 --> 00:09:08,132
hoy!

183
00:09:08,333 --> 00:09:09,733
hoy!

184
00:09:10,166 --> 00:09:11,098
hoy!

185
00:09:11,299 --> 00:09:12,332
hoy!

186
00:09:12,533 --> 00:09:13,399
(Archie) for god's sake,

187
00:09:13,600 --> 00:09:15,666
don't torture yourself like this, Laura.

188
00:09:16,466 --> 00:09:17,933
[Julia sobbing]

189
00:09:19,799 --> 00:09:21,933
no one will ever know
how much I loved him.

190
00:09:24,933 --> 00:09:26,700
he was my earth, my moon,

191
00:09:29,166 --> 00:09:31,366
all the stars in the firmament.

192
00:09:41,033 --> 00:09:42,600
farewell, my love.

193
00:09:45,799 --> 00:09:47,433
[audience applauding]

194
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:52,066
bravo! bravo!

195
00:09:52,799 --> 00:09:54,500
[people laughing]

196
00:10:06,733 --> 00:10:08,700
no, there's nothing left for me now

197
00:10:08,933 --> 00:10:10,965
but to tour Canada and Australia,

198
00:10:11,166 --> 00:10:12,566
god help me.

199
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:14,765
nonsense, miss Lambert.

200
00:10:14,966 --> 00:10:16,165
it's not nonsense.

201
00:10:16,366 --> 00:10:16,966
[sighing]

202
00:10:17,100 --> 00:10:19,166
I've decided to retire
and let myself go.

203
00:10:20,133 --> 00:10:22,666
I'll have potatoes for lunch
and potatoes for dinner.

204
00:10:26,266 --> 00:10:27,866
beer. god, I love beer!

205
00:10:29,500 --> 00:10:31,666
and treacle pudding and
cherry tart and cream.

206
00:10:32,700 --> 00:10:34,833
cream, cream, cream, cream, cream...

207
00:10:35,033 --> 00:10:36,032
[breathing deeply]

208
00:10:36,233 --> 00:10:37,032
as god is my judge,

209
00:10:37,233 --> 00:10:39,098
I'll never eat a lettuce leaf again.

210
00:10:39,299 --> 00:10:40,198
[doorbell ringing]

211
00:10:40,399 --> 00:10:42,500
oh, god, I bet I know who that is.

212
00:10:45,133 --> 00:10:46,833
good afternoon, Evie.

213
00:10:47,933 --> 00:10:49,899
oh, Mrs. de vries, what a surprise.

214
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:52,333
uh, I hope this isn't inconvenient

215
00:10:52,833 --> 00:10:54,532
but I have to see miss Lambert

216
00:10:54,733 --> 00:10:55,765
on a business matter.

217
00:10:55,966 --> 00:10:58,066
she isn't having one
of her afternoon naps,

218
00:10:58,799 --> 00:11:00,266
is she?

219
00:11:02,600 --> 00:11:03,932
wait a minute.

220
00:11:04,133 --> 00:11:05,600
[door squeaking]

221
00:11:06,433 --> 00:11:07,698
guess who's here.

222
00:11:07,899 --> 00:11:08,632
show her in.

223
00:11:08,833 --> 00:11:10,565
business, she says, but isn't it funny

224
00:11:10,766 --> 00:11:12,365
how she always manages
to time her visits

225
00:11:12,566 --> 00:11:14,232
when you're lying stark bollock naked.

226
00:11:14,433 --> 00:11:16,733
enough of that, you dirty-minded slut.

227
00:11:17,933 --> 00:11:19,533
show her in.

228
00:11:21,766 --> 00:11:22,632
Mrs. de vries.

229
00:11:22,833 --> 00:11:23,765
(dolly) Julia, darling.

230
00:11:23,966 --> 00:11:25,600
dolly, dear. hmm.

231
00:11:26,666 --> 00:11:27,632
oh, I'm so sorry.

232
00:11:27,833 --> 00:11:30,366
I always seem to call when
you're--you're otherwise engaged.

233
00:11:31,566 --> 00:11:32,332
[laughing]

234
00:11:32,533 --> 00:11:33,532
tea? lovely.

235
00:11:33,733 --> 00:11:35,966
ignore me. I'll--I'll just
sit here quiet as a lamb

236
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:39,166
until you're done.

237
00:11:40,333 --> 00:11:40,999
so Evie said

238
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:43,233
something about business. hmm?

239
00:11:45,666 --> 00:11:46,532
what? oh, yes.

240
00:11:46,733 --> 00:11:49,066
um, Michael tells me you
want to close the play.

241
00:11:49,933 --> 00:11:51,899
my husband's a devious little runt.

242
00:11:53,299 --> 00:11:54,732
oh, that's unfair.

243
00:11:54,933 --> 00:11:56,932
he was perfectly right to consult me.

244
00:11:57,133 --> 00:11:59,000
we're partners. the 3 of us.

245
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:00,732
a perfect combination.

246
00:12:00,933 --> 00:12:02,799
my money, his know-how, your genius.

247
00:12:03,899 --> 00:12:05,499
I'm exhausted, dolly.

248
00:12:05,700 --> 00:12:06,300
[grunts]

249
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:08,232
I feel twice my age which makes me 90.

250
00:12:08,433 --> 00:12:10,833
I'm bored. life has
nothing in store for me.

251
00:12:11,166 --> 00:12:12,698
you mean that or are you acting?

252
00:12:12,899 --> 00:12:14,732
I never know when you're acting.

253
00:12:14,933 --> 00:12:16,198
I'm not acting.

254
00:12:16,399 --> 00:12:17,299
I'm near to having a breakdown.

255
00:12:17,500 --> 00:12:19,733
I feel as though my
life's come to an end.

256
00:12:20,166 --> 00:12:21,799
all right. all right.

257
00:12:22,299 --> 00:12:23,399
all done.

258
00:12:23,600 --> 00:12:25,466
oh, thank you, you're a dear.

259
00:12:27,500 --> 00:12:28,899
uh.

260
00:12:29,633 --> 00:12:31,666
are you really near a breakdown, Julia?

261
00:12:33,033 --> 00:12:34,833
oh, I don't know. I don't know.

262
00:12:36,899 --> 00:12:39,200
I'm in such an odd state at the moment.

263
00:12:39,666 --> 00:12:40,432
[inhaling]

264
00:12:40,633 --> 00:12:41,233
it's as if...

265
00:12:41,399 --> 00:12:43,799
it's as if the curtain's
come down on act 1,

266
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,066
but I have no idea
what happens in act 2.

267
