313
00:14:42,199 --> 00:14:44,000
I'm on my way I'm on my way

314
00:14:44,233 --> 00:14:46,133
I'm busy 'cause I'm on my way

315
00:14:46,833 --> 00:14:48,500
[people applauding]

316
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:50,566
thank you.

317
00:14:51,399 --> 00:14:52,833
thank you.

318
00:14:53,566 --> 00:14:55,066
Julia Lambert.

319
00:15:04,533 --> 00:15:06,333
the champagne now, my lord?

320
00:15:06,866 --> 00:15:08,299
thank you, Antoine.

321
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:10,265
and for you, madame Lambert?

322
00:15:10,466 --> 00:15:12,299
I'd prefer beer but I mustn't,

323
00:15:12,500 --> 00:15:14,233
so I'll make do with bubbly.

324
00:15:14,466 --> 00:15:16,033
thank you.

325
00:15:17,100 --> 00:15:19,033
[giggling] it's for you. open it.

326
00:15:20,133 --> 00:15:21,666
[woman singing]

327
00:15:25,666 --> 00:15:26,299
oh.

328
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:28,233
it's a portrait of Clairon.

329
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:30,232
she was a great actress,

330
00:15:30,433 --> 00:15:32,399
and I believe you
have many of her gifts.

331
00:15:33,066 --> 00:15:34,733
Charles, you are sweet.

332
00:15:36,033 --> 00:15:37,899
I thought you might like it.

333
00:15:39,533 --> 00:15:41,566
it's by way of being a parting present.

334
00:15:41,833 --> 00:15:42,998
you're going away?

335
00:15:43,199 --> 00:15:45,399
no. but I shan't be seeing you anymore.

336
00:15:46,133 --> 00:15:47,733
oh, Charles, not again.

337
00:15:48,166 --> 00:15:48,766
[inhaling]

338
00:15:48,733 --> 00:15:50,833
no. this is becoming a ritual. why?

339
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:53,699
we have such a beautiful
friendship, Julia.

340
00:15:54,500 --> 00:15:56,799
it's unique in my
experience, but people talk.

341
00:15:59,100 --> 00:16:00,733
they don't understand.

342
00:16:00,933 --> 00:16:02,899
and even though we know the truth,

343
00:16:03,366 --> 00:16:04,865
if we go on seeing one another,

344
00:16:05,066 --> 00:16:06,765
there will be a terrible scandal.

345
00:16:06,966 --> 00:16:07,665
no, there won't.

346
00:16:07,866 --> 00:16:09,966
Michael and I lead separate lives.

347
00:16:10,433 --> 00:16:12,566
that's why we're so happily married.

348
00:16:13,233 --> 00:16:14,733
more or less.

349
00:16:15,133 --> 00:16:17,233
jumped-up little tart,
that's what she is.

350
00:16:18,266 --> 00:16:20,133
never stops acting, on-stage or off.

351
00:16:20,533 --> 00:16:22,333
she's just one big pose.

352
00:16:23,166 --> 00:16:23,766
dashed pretty.

353
00:16:23,933 --> 00:16:26,033
shut up, Rupert, don't
show your ignorance.

354
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:28,699
I know all about her.

355
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:29,600
we were both born

356
00:16:29,699 --> 00:16:31,866
in the channel islands, jersey.

357
00:16:32,066 --> 00:16:34,166
her father was our
doctor. a jersey doctor!

358
00:16:36,233 --> 00:16:38,233
you can't get more common than that.

359
00:16:41,066 --> 00:16:42,866
it's only common sense, darling.

360
00:16:44,299 --> 00:16:46,133
I don't want to lose you.

361
00:16:46,533 --> 00:16:48,533
I--I have few
friends. real friends.

362
00:16:51,699 --> 00:16:53,098
you're the only person in my life

363
00:16:53,299 --> 00:16:55,533
with whom I can be entirely myself.

364
00:16:56,199 --> 00:16:58,233
I'm terribly low at the moment.

365
00:16:59,500 --> 00:17:00,565
I--I
need you.

366
00:17:00,766 --> 00:17:02,799
let's go on seeing each other. please.

367
00:17:03,533 --> 00:17:06,200
uh, please forgive us intruding
like this, miss Lambert.

368
00:17:07,333 --> 00:17:09,633
my friend and I are
such very great admirers.

369
00:17:10,233 --> 00:17:12,099
and I wonder... do you remember me?

370
00:17:13,133 --> 00:17:15,033
Florence Coltraine, isn't it?

371
00:17:15,233 --> 00:17:16,432
[whispers] correct.

372
00:17:16,633 --> 00:17:18,766
Rupert and I want you
to settle an argument.

373
00:17:19,066 --> 00:17:21,200
I think I used to know
your father in jersey.

374
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:24,098
he was a doctor, wasn't he?

375
00:17:24,299 --> 00:17:26,533
he used to come to
our house quite often.

376
00:17:26,866 --> 00:17:27,865
actually, he was a vet.

377
00:17:28,066 --> 00:17:29,299
he used to go to your house

378
00:17:29,500 --> 00:17:30,699
to deliver the bitches.

379
00:17:30,900 --> 00:17:32,633
the house was full of them.

380
00:17:33,633 --> 00:17:35,866
life is just a bowl of cherries

381
00:17:37,200 --> 00:17:39,333
don't take it serious
life's too mysterious

382
00:17:41,966 --> 00:17:44,200
you work, you save you worry so

383
00:17:46,366 --> 00:17:48,500
but you can't take
your dough when you go

384
00:17:52,366 --> 00:17:52,966
[exclaims]

385
00:17:52,866 --> 00:17:55,200
I'm sorry, I didn't
mean to frighten you.

386
00:17:55,766 --> 00:17:57,066
t-o-m.

387
00:17:58,133 --> 00:17:58,932
you remember.

388
00:17:59,133 --> 00:18:01,033
did you like
the--the flowers?

389
00:18:01,433 --> 00:18:03,500
oh, Mr. Thomas fennel, Tavistock square.

390
00:18:06,133 --> 00:18:07,465
yes, of course, thank you.

391
00:18:07,666 --> 00:18:09,766
well, uh, I couldn't
decide between a single rose

392
00:18:10,366 --> 00:18:11,598
and every flower in the store.

393
00:18:11,799 --> 00:18:13,966
is that why you're here
at this time of night?

394
00:18:14,333 --> 00:18:16,332
to find out if I received the flowers?

395
00:18:16,533 --> 00:18:18,700
no. you see, I don't have a phone yet.

396
00:18:19,133 --> 00:18:20,432
[door opening] and I...

397
00:18:20,633 --> 00:18:21,865
[Wilson clearing throat]

398
00:18:22,066 --> 00:18:22,666
um...

399
00:18:22,733 --> 00:18:24,866
you wouldn't come to tea
with me one day, would you?

400
00:18:27,833 --> 00:18:29,433
I don't see why not.

401
00:18:29,700 --> 00:18:31,032
will you really?

402
00:18:31,233 --> 00:18:32,098
how about next Friday?

403
00:18:32,299 --> 00:18:34,299
138 Tavistock square, 4:30?

404
00:18:35,933 --> 00:18:36,533
[laughing]

405
00:18:36,733 --> 00:18:38,799
all right. I'll be there.

406
00:18:39,200 --> 00:18:40,965
gee, that's swell. see you then.

407
00:18:41,166 --> 00:18:43,799
the sweet things in life
to you were just loaned

408
00:18:45,099 --> 00:18:47,700
so how gonna you lose
what you've never owned?

409
00:18:49,933 --> 00:18:52,166
life is just a bowl of cherries

410
00:18:53,266 --> 00:18:53,932
[tom and Julia laughing]

411
00:18:54,133 --> 00:18:56,266
so live and laugh at it all

412
00:18:57,066 --> 00:18:59,465
(chorus) life is just a bowl of cherries

413
00:18:59,666 --> 00:19:01,799
don't make it serious
life's too mysterious

414
00:19:02,933 --> 00:19:05,132
you work, you save you worry so

415
00:19:05,333 --> 00:19:07,599
but you can't take your
dough when you go go

416
00:19:08,733 --> 00:19:11,033
keep on repeating "it's the berries"

417
00:19:11,466 --> 00:19:13,633
the strongest oak must fall

418
00:19:17,333 --> 00:19:17,965
oh?

419
00:19:18,166 --> 00:19:19,700
I saw you drive up.

420
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:21,465
I'm afraid I'm on the 3rd floor.

421
00:19:21,666 --> 00:19:22,999
I hope you don't mind.

422
00:19:23,200 --> 00:19:24,165
and if I do?

423
00:19:24,366 --> 00:19:25,866
[both chuckle]

424
00:19:31,066 --> 00:19:32,065
we're there.

425
00:19:32,266 --> 00:19:33,799
thank god for that.

426
00:19:34,033 --> 00:19:34,965
[door squeaking]

427
00:19:35,166 --> 00:19:36,633
[Julia panting]

428
00:19:40,900 --> 00:19:42,299
[laughs]

429
00:19:47,233 --> 00:19:49,133
the gas ring's in the bathroom.

430
00:19:49,333 --> 00:19:50,599
oh.

431
00:19:50,866 --> 00:19:51,732
it isn't the Ritz, but it's home.

432
00:19:51,933 --> 00:19:54,266
no, it's--it's
charming. it's so London.

433
00:19:55,033 --> 00:19:57,099
it reminds me of my early days.

434
00:19:57,366 --> 00:19:58,799
[laughing]

435
00:19:59,299 --> 00:20:01,333
I have to put coins in the gas meter.

436
00:20:01,599 --> 00:20:02,965
oh, yes, so did I.

437
00:20:03,166 --> 00:20:04,633
[both laughing]

438
00:20:05,466 --> 00:20:07,500
have some cake. I bought it specially.

439
00:20:08,166 --> 00:20:09,500
oh.

440
00:20:10,166 --> 00:20:11,833
I shouldn't, but I will.

441
00:20:12,266 --> 00:20:13,599
[laughs]

442
00:20:14,733 --> 00:20:16,299
[sighing]

443
00:20:17,299 --> 00:20:19,466
you know something? you
ought to be in movies.

444
00:20:19,833 --> 00:20:22,033
real actresses don't make films.

445
00:20:23,566 --> 00:20:25,366
but beautiful actresses do.

446
00:20:26,200 --> 00:20:26,800
hmm.

447
00:20:26,933 --> 00:20:29,200
well, I saw you in nobody's
perfect on Broadway.

448
00:20:29,966 --> 00:20:31,165
I was 14 at the time.

449
00:20:31,366 --> 00:20:33,132
I wish you hadn't told me that.

450
00:20:33,333 --> 00:20:33,933
[both laughing]

451
00:20:33,866 --> 00:20:36,266
I stood outside the stage door
and, uh, I got your autograph.

452
00:20:37,099 --> 00:20:38,865
you asked me my name. I told you.

453
00:20:39,066 --> 00:20:40,833
you knew how to spell it then.

454
00:20:44,533 --> 00:20:46,000
[both laughing]

455
00:20:48,166 --> 00:20:49,633
what's so funny?

456
00:20:51,733 --> 00:20:53,599
you remind me of something.

457
00:20:54,200 --> 00:20:55,666
what is it?

458
00:20:57,666 --> 00:20:59,700
my husband. in a scene we had to play.

459
00:21:01,133 --> 00:21:03,033
he didn't know how to sit down.

460
00:21:03,700 --> 00:21:04,999
[both laughing]

461
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:07,299
Jimmie made him do it
over and over again.

462
00:21:10,666 --> 00:21:11,765
uh, I can't stay long.

463
00:21:11,966 --> 00:21:14,033
I must have a nap before my performance.

464
00:21:14,900 --> 00:21:16,699
but you've only just arrived.

465
00:21:16,900 --> 00:21:18,799
and you--you can't
go without, uh,

466
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:21,166
without, well, seeing the view.

467
00:21:21,933 --> 00:21:22,799
it's really great.

468
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:25,166
if you just come over to the window...

469
00:21:38,700 --> 00:21:40,032
isn't it terrific?

470
00:21:40,233 --> 00:21:40,965
(tom) I just love London.

471
00:21:41,166 --> 00:21:43,299
it's so big, but it's
also kind of friendly.

472
00:21:43,599 --> 00:21:45,799
and all those people,
each with their own lives.

473
00:21:46,700 --> 00:21:48,132
I can't explain it.

474
00:21:48,333 --> 00:21:50,933
when I first came to London,
I stood in Piccadilly circus

475
00:21:53,299 --> 00:21:54,098
looking at the lights

476
00:21:54,299 --> 00:21:55,665
and the people and the taxis,

477
00:21:55,866 --> 00:21:57,599
and I said out loud:

478
00:21:58,033 --> 00:22:00,166
"one day I'm going to conquer you."

479
00:22:00,799 --> 00:22:02,366
and you have.

480
00:22:02,766 --> 00:22:04,333
have I?
I wonder--

481
00:22:27,533 --> 00:22:28,898
[sighing]

482
00:22:29,099 --> 00:22:30,633
look at my hair.

483
00:22:31,299 --> 00:22:32,766
[Julia panting]

484
00:22:33,466 --> 00:22:34,898
uh, here.

485
00:22:35,099 --> 00:22:36,366
oh?

486
00:22:36,666 --> 00:22:38,099
thank you.

487
00:22:41,099 --> 00:22:43,233
and I thought you were
such a shy young man.

488
00:22:45,566 --> 00:22:47,666
when am I-- when am
I gonna see you again?

489
00:22:48,733 --> 00:22:50,433
you want to see me again?

490
00:22:51,599 --> 00:22:52,832
what do you think?

491
00:22:53,033 --> 00:22:55,000
I'll ring you up one of these days.

492
00:22:55,566 --> 00:22:57,066
uh, my hat...

493
00:22:57,733 --> 00:22:59,299
oh, uh...

494
00:23:01,500 --> 00:23:03,500
good. well, uh, I have a phone now.

495
00:23:03,733 --> 00:23:05,599
and the number's museum-4516.

496
00:23:06,299 --> 00:23:08,099
so promise you'll call soon.

497
00:23:08,400 --> 00:23:09,933
on my honor.

498
00:23:10,133 --> 00:23:12,099
[laughs] you know, don't come down.

499
00:23:12,299 --> 00:23:14,000
I can see myself out.

500
00:23:18,900 --> 00:23:20,398
[birds twittering]

501
00:23:20,599 --> 00:23:23,099
for Christ's sake, Julia,
what do you think you're doing?

502
00:23:23,466 --> 00:23:24,765
you're supposed to be playing a whore,

503
00:23:24,966 --> 00:23:27,333
not a schoolgirl with a
crush on her gym mistress.

504
00:23:28,166 --> 00:23:28,766
you kissed him

505
00:23:28,799 --> 00:23:31,000
as if you were frightened
of catching his cold.

506
00:23:31,400 --> 00:23:32,432
when you kiss, you should feel

507
00:23:32,633 --> 00:23:34,799
as if your bones are
melting inside your body.

508
00:23:35,766 --> 00:23:36,366
tongues, darling,

509
00:23:36,566 --> 00:23:38,065
that's what it's about, tongues.

510
00:23:38,266 --> 00:23:38,898
now, I know you're a virgin.

511
00:23:39,099 --> 00:23:41,299
don't give me the waterworks,
Julia, I'm too old for that.

512
00:23:41,500 --> 00:23:44,166
you're a virgin, so what you have
to do is find a handsome young man,

513
00:23:45,233 --> 00:23:47,333
like your juvenile
man, Michael Gosselyn.

514
00:23:47,933 --> 00:23:48,533
go back to your rooms,

515
00:23:48,633 --> 00:23:51,033
take your clothes off, lie
on the bed, open your legs

516
00:23:51,299 --> 00:23:53,566
and ask him to give it to
you hot, sweet and strong.

517
00:23:54,233 --> 00:23:56,666
if that doesn't improve your
acting, then nothing will.

518
00:23:57,299 --> 00:23:59,000
right, let's do it again.

519
00:24:01,500 --> 00:24:02,966
[Julia laughing]

520
00:24:05,933 --> 00:24:07,400
what's so funny?

521
00:24:18,800 --> 00:24:19,400
[sighing]

522
00:24:19,500 --> 00:24:21,467
I feel as though
I'm a 2-year-old.

523
00:24:22,500 --> 00:24:24,534
that's 88 years you've lost in a week.

524
00:24:26,100 --> 00:24:27,099
[giggling]

525
00:24:27,300 --> 00:24:28,799
tell us the secret,

526
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:30,867
we'll bottle it and make a fortune.

527
00:24:33,700 --> 00:24:34,466
hmm.

528
00:24:34,667 --> 00:24:36,167
[door closing]

529
00:24:41,967 --> 00:24:44,167
damn it all, miss Lambert,
you don't look so bad.

530
00:24:47,333 --> 00:24:49,333
you can go on
playing 25-year-olds,

531
00:24:51,167 --> 00:24:53,200
30-year-olds for a
good long time yet.

532
00:24:54,367 --> 00:24:55,867
and then what?

