whoo!

534
00:24:56,833 --> 00:24:58,833
mothers, grandmothers and old maids.

535
00:24:59,333 --> 00:24:59,933
[snorting]

536
00:24:59,767 --> 00:25:02,000
bugger playwrights.
can't write for women.

537
00:25:02,634 --> 00:25:04,500
they're all men, that's the trouble.

538
00:25:05,100 --> 00:25:06,732
[telephone ringing]

539
00:25:06,933 --> 00:25:08,500
[sighing]

540
00:25:15,300 --> 00:25:16,333
yes?

541
00:25:16,534 --> 00:25:17,999
good morning.

542
00:25:18,200 --> 00:25:19,700
[Julia laughing]

543
00:25:20,467 --> 00:25:21,833
t-o-m.

544
00:25:22,200 --> 00:25:23,499
you promised to call me.

545
00:25:23,700 --> 00:25:24,899
(Julia) give a girl a chance.

546
00:25:25,100 --> 00:25:27,767
(tom) when am I going to see you again?

547
00:25:28,034 --> 00:25:30,300
as soon as I have a moment to spare.

548
00:25:30,934 --> 00:25:33,100
come to tea after the matinee.

549
00:25:34,167 --> 00:25:36,132
oh, I'm not falling for that one again.

550
00:25:36,333 --> 00:25:38,600
how about dinner after the show then?

551
00:25:41,267 --> 00:25:42,833
if you insist.

552
00:25:45,833 --> 00:25:47,333
I do.

553
00:25:47,900 --> 00:25:49,299
[piano playing]

554
00:25:49,500 --> 00:25:51,333
on the silver screen

555
00:25:51,534 --> 00:25:54,100
he melts her foolish
heart in every single scene

556
00:25:55,767 --> 00:25:58,300
although she's quite
aware that here and there

557
00:26:00,400 --> 00:26:02,333
are traces of the cad about the boy

558
00:26:05,500 --> 00:26:06,566
[laughing]

559
00:26:06,767 --> 00:26:08,667
lord knows she's not a fool girl

560
00:26:11,734 --> 00:26:13,534
she really shouldn't care

561
00:26:14,933 --> 00:26:17,267
lord knows she's not a school girl

562
00:26:17,500 --> 00:26:19,834
in the flurry of her first affair

563
00:26:23,434 --> 00:26:25,667
will it ever cloy this odd diversity

564
00:26:27,834 --> 00:26:29,934
of misery and joy I told them

565
00:26:33,133 --> 00:26:35,167
look, there's lord Crumley over there.

566
00:26:35,900 --> 00:26:37,532
and I think that's lady Laweston.

567
00:26:37,733 --> 00:26:39,899
what have you been reading,  Debrett's?

568
00:26:40,100 --> 00:26:42,000
Debrett's? no,  the tatler.

569
00:26:42,367 --> 00:26:42,967
[laughing]

570
00:26:42,867 --> 00:26:45,066
oh, you have to know who's
who to get on in this town.

571
00:26:45,267 --> 00:26:47,200
oh, you want to get on, do you?

572
00:26:47,500 --> 00:26:49,500
I want to get on you, Julia.

573
00:26:49,767 --> 00:26:51,367
don't be disgusting.

574
00:26:51,567 --> 00:26:53,034
but I want you.

575
00:26:54,633 --> 00:26:56,032
I do.

576
00:26:56,233 --> 00:26:57,133
[glasses clinking]

577
00:26:57,334 --> 00:26:59,534
you're the loveliest girl that one

578
00:27:02,334 --> 00:27:03,499
I want you.

579
00:27:03,700 --> 00:27:04,532
[giggling]

580
00:27:04,733 --> 00:27:07,034
your conversation's
frightfully limited, tom.

581
00:27:08,667 --> 00:27:09,599
dance with me.

582
00:27:09,800 --> 00:27:11,467
what time is it?

583
00:27:12,167 --> 00:27:14,334
oh, well, uh, I... I
forgot to put on my watch.

584
00:27:16,567 --> 00:27:18,100
have you pawned it?

585
00:27:19,100 --> 00:27:20,532
no, no, I just, uh,

586
00:27:20,733 --> 00:27:22,767
I--I dressed in
rather a hurry tonight.

587
00:27:24,667 --> 00:27:26,500
they'll never believe me

588
00:27:29,167 --> 00:27:31,034
they'll never believe me

589
00:27:33,434 --> 00:27:35,767
that from this great big world

590
00:27:37,700 --> 00:27:39,467
you've chosen

591
00:27:40,833 --> 00:27:42,267
[laughing]

592
00:27:47,434 --> 00:27:49,133
[Julia screaming]

593
00:27:50,833 --> 00:27:52,500
[continues laughing]

594
00:27:55,200 --> 00:27:57,034
he treated you like a tart.

595
00:27:57,600 --> 00:27:59,534
which of course is what you are.

596
00:28:02,034 --> 00:28:04,133
(Julia) he was my earth, my moon,

597
00:28:07,300 --> 00:28:09,567
and all the stars in the firmament.

598
00:28:16,333 --> 00:28:18,800
[whispering] the photo's
in the wrong place!

599
00:28:23,434 --> 00:28:25,000
farewell, my love.

600
00:28:35,034 --> 00:28:36,967
you were wonderful tonight, my darling.

601
00:28:38,134 --> 00:28:38,899
[whooping]

602
00:28:39,100 --> 00:28:40,366
bloody marvelous.

603
00:28:40,567 --> 00:28:42,167
you almost made me cry.

604
00:28:42,767 --> 00:28:43,799
only almost?

605
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:45,899
I'll kill whoever set the photo.

606
00:28:46,100 --> 00:28:46,700
thanks, Archie.

607
00:28:46,700 --> 00:28:48,499
and what've you done to your eyes?

608
00:28:48,700 --> 00:28:49,933
hmm? some new makeup?

609
00:28:50,134 --> 00:28:52,134
I've never seen them
shine like that before.

610
00:28:52,634 --> 00:28:53,999
your call, Mr. Dexter.

611
00:28:54,200 --> 00:28:54,800
hmm.

612
00:28:54,933 --> 00:28:55,633
[Archie laughing]

613
00:28:55,834 --> 00:28:57,967
sorry about the photo,
it won't happen again.

614
00:28:58,933 --> 00:28:59,799
hmm.

615
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:01,566
your call, miss Lambert.

616
00:29:01,767 --> 00:29:03,433
you're forgiven.

617
00:29:03,667 --> 00:29:05,300
[audience applauding]

618
00:29:07,367 --> 00:29:09,100
what's the matter with her?

619
00:29:10,034 --> 00:29:11,199
[Julia exclaiming]

620
00:29:11,400 --> 00:29:13,000
darling, Julia.

621
00:29:15,700 --> 00:29:17,634
you were quite wonderful tonight.

622
00:29:17,834 --> 00:29:19,532
I'll say. absolutely first-rate.

623
00:29:19,733 --> 00:29:20,633
thank you.

624
00:29:20,834 --> 00:29:23,233
yes, I believe I was
firing on all cylinders.

625
00:29:23,534 --> 00:29:25,834
and I'm starving, absolutely ravenous.

626
00:29:26,500 --> 00:29:28,600
Evie, what have we
got for supper tonight?

627
00:29:28,967 --> 00:29:29,567
tripe and onions.

628
00:29:29,667 --> 00:29:31,900
oh, how divine. I
adore tripe and onions.

629
00:29:33,500 --> 00:29:35,566
Michael, Michael, if you love me,

630
00:29:35,767 --> 00:29:37,667
if you've got any spark of tenderness

631
00:29:38,267 --> 00:29:39,666
in that hard heart of yours,

632
00:29:39,867 --> 00:29:41,767
let me have a bottle of beer.

633
00:29:42,034 --> 00:29:42,666
beer? yes.

634
00:29:42,867 --> 00:29:44,433
Julia. just this once.

635
00:29:44,634 --> 00:29:46,400
oh, Evie, that's for you.

636
00:29:46,667 --> 00:29:47,532
uh, please?

637
00:29:47,733 --> 00:29:49,667
Julia, I think it's a damn shame.

638
00:29:50,034 --> 00:29:50,699
(Julia) what is?

639
00:29:50,900 --> 00:29:53,200
well, that you're taking the play off.

640
00:29:53,534 --> 00:29:54,266
the good news is,

641
00:29:54,467 --> 00:29:55,466
I've found an Italian company

642
00:29:55,667 --> 00:29:57,333
who wants the theatre for 3 months,

643
00:29:57,534 --> 00:29:59,666
so I said they could have it. hmm. mmm.

644
00:29:59,867 --> 00:30:01,933
I'm sure your mother's
as excited as I am

645
00:30:02,233 --> 00:30:03,566
at the thought of being with you.

646
00:30:03,767 --> 00:30:05,699
we'll have such fun at my place, Julia.

647
00:30:05,900 --> 00:30:07,834
you could do anything you like.

648
00:30:08,067 --> 00:30:09,032
rest. anything.

649
00:30:09,233 --> 00:30:10,966
I've changed my mind. I don't know why,

650
00:30:11,167 --> 00:30:13,667
but I'm beginning to  enjoy
myself again. oh, but--

651
00:30:14,167 --> 00:30:15,299
let's run through the summer

652
00:30:15,500 --> 00:30:17,500
and then find something
new for the autumn.

653
00:30:17,733 --> 00:30:19,767
but I've... I-I've...
I've told the Italians.

654
00:30:20,433 --> 00:30:21,499
then un-tell them.

655
00:30:21,700 --> 00:30:23,733
and I was so looking forward to France.

656
00:30:24,534 --> 00:30:26,267
stars will be stars.

657
00:30:31,034 --> 00:30:32,333
I forgot.

658
00:30:32,534 --> 00:30:33,466
what?

659
00:30:33,667 --> 00:30:35,167
hmm...

660
00:30:38,834 --> 00:30:40,267
[exclaims]

661
00:30:48,267 --> 00:30:49,900
oh, my god. a cartier.

662
00:30:50,600 --> 00:30:52,600
well spotted. when's your birthday?

663
00:30:53,433 --> 00:30:54,399
November 20.

664
00:30:54,600 --> 00:30:55,433
hmm.

665
00:30:55,634 --> 00:30:56,234
happy birthday.

666
00:30:56,233 --> 00:30:57,966
uh, but it's not November 20.

667
00:30:58,167 --> 00:31:00,067
don't be so pedantic. open it.

668
00:31:03,067 --> 00:31:05,300
oh, that's the one thing
I've wanted my whole life.

669
00:31:06,367 --> 00:31:07,299
thank you.

670
00:31:07,500 --> 00:31:09,067
[giggles]

671
00:31:09,567 --> 00:31:10,333
uh, geez, it's lousy

672
00:31:10,534 --> 00:31:12,667
I can't give you anything in return.

673
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,167
give me that watch you
pawned to buy me supper.

674
00:31:15,800 --> 00:31:17,834
have you redeemed it yet? ah! thanks.

675
00:31:21,967 --> 00:31:23,800
it'll amuse me to wear it.

676
00:31:24,334 --> 00:31:25,900
I love you, Julia.

677
00:31:31,167 --> 00:31:31,767
[sighing]

678
00:31:31,800 --> 00:31:34,000
this is total insanity.
I'm old enough to be...

679
00:31:36,667 --> 00:31:38,100
[laughing]

680
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:40,733
god, I'm a fool,

681
00:31:41,933 --> 00:31:43,600
I'm such a bloody fool.

682
00:31:49,100 --> 00:31:50,967
good morning, Evie. where's my wife?

683
00:31:51,633 --> 00:31:52,566
in your study.

684
00:31:52,767 --> 00:31:54,667
my study? mmm-hmm.

685
00:31:55,300 --> 00:31:56,833
what's she doing there?

686
00:31:57,034 --> 00:31:58,567
exercising.

687
00:32:00,700 --> 00:32:02,300
exercising?

688
00:32:03,233 --> 00:32:04,600
[grunting]

689
00:32:04,800 --> 00:32:05,400
what are you doing?

690
00:32:05,600 --> 00:32:07,834
swimming the channel, what
do you think I'm doing?

691
00:32:10,133 --> 00:32:11,432
yeah, but why?

692
00:32:11,633 --> 00:32:12,233
[panting]

693
00:32:12,133 --> 00:32:14,300
miss Phillips said my
tummy needed tightening,

694
00:32:15,767 --> 00:32:17,400
so I'm tightening it.

695
00:32:18,900 --> 00:32:20,467
[grunting]

696
00:32:21,567 --> 00:32:22,932
oh.

697
00:32:23,133 --> 00:32:23,733
[grunting]

698
00:32:23,600 --> 00:32:25,667
oh, yes, I had a thought.

699
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:27,499
we should take a country house

700
00:32:27,700 --> 00:32:28,766
for the summer.

701
00:32:28,967 --> 00:32:30,667
what do you think?

702
00:32:31,267 --> 00:32:32,733
[Julia grunting]

703
00:32:36,167 --> 00:32:37,166
I'll talk to you later.

704
00:32:37,367 --> 00:32:37,967
[continues grunting]

705
00:32:38,034 --> 00:32:40,834
(Michael) so do you think a house
for the summer's a good idea?

706
00:32:41,900 --> 00:32:42,866
yes.

707
00:32:43,067 --> 00:32:43,667
golf, swimming, tennis.

708
00:32:43,734 --> 00:32:45,566
it'll be especially good
for Roger. he loves golf.

709
00:32:45,767 --> 00:32:48,467
then he'll have to decide
what's he gonna do with his life.

710
00:32:48,734 --> 00:32:50,632
I think he should go to university.

711
00:32:50,833 --> 00:32:52,967
he doesn't want to,
and we shouldn't insist.

712
00:32:53,767 --> 00:32:55,267
it's his life.

713
00:32:55,600 --> 00:32:57,232
oh, yes, I had another idea.

714
00:32:57,433 --> 00:32:59,900
you remember that young
chap I introduced you to?

715
00:33:00,867 --> 00:33:01,467
which young chap?

716
00:33:01,667 --> 00:33:03,866
that American. good-looking fellow.

717
00:33:04,067 --> 00:33:04,667
remember?

718
00:33:04,867 --> 00:33:06,199
[clearing throat] no.

719
00:33:06,400 --> 00:33:08,166
he wants to learn the business.

720
00:33:08,367 --> 00:33:09,599
tom fennel's his name.

721
00:33:09,800 --> 00:33:11,667
American, you must remember.

722
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:13,199
vaguely.

723
00:33:13,400 --> 00:33:15,333
well, he's frightfully good at his job.

724
00:33:15,767 --> 00:33:16,666
he's a wizard with money.

725
00:33:16,867 --> 00:33:18,933
lots of American ideas for avoiding tax.

726
00:33:21,200 --> 00:33:22,199
what about him?

727
00:33:22,400 --> 00:33:23,833
well, I thought we might invite him down

728
00:33:24,034 --> 00:33:26,600
for a couple of weeks to
spend his holiday with us.

729
00:33:28,067 --> 00:33:29,333
why would we want to do that?

730
00:33:29,534 --> 00:33:31,634
he'll be company for Roger.

731
00:33:32,067 --> 00:33:33,132
he's only a bit older.

732
00:33:33,333 --> 00:33:35,600
Roger will like him, I'm sure of it.

733
00:33:36,600 --> 00:33:38,067
shall I ask him?

734
00:33:38,300 --> 00:33:39,700
hmm.

735
00:33:40,333 --> 00:33:41,600
ah!

736
00:33:42,267 --> 00:33:44,300
(Julia) remind me to keep exercising.

737
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:49,034
so, will you come and stay?

738
00:33:49,234 --> 00:33:51,467
Michael says the house is
frightfully comfortable.

739
00:33:52,200 --> 00:33:52,999
probably not.

740
00:33:53,200 --> 00:33:55,134
I'm going abroad for a couple of months.

741
00:33:55,800 --> 00:33:56,400
(Julia) what fun.

742
00:33:56,600 --> 00:33:58,199
well, you'll be busy, won't you?

743
00:33:58,400 --> 00:34:00,333
looking for a new play, reading scripts.

744
00:34:01,767 --> 00:34:03,400
so, what do you think?

745
00:34:04,034 --> 00:34:06,034
he hasn't done justice to your eyes.

746
00:34:07,534 --> 00:34:08,366
as a matter of fact,

747
00:34:08,567 --> 00:34:10,232
there is a play that interests me.

748
00:34:10,433 --> 00:34:11,132
it's about an older woman

749
00:34:11,333 --> 00:34:13,367
who has an affair with a younger man.

750
00:34:13,800 --> 00:34:15,199
oh, a farce.

751
00:34:15,400 --> 00:34:16,599
why do you say that?

752
00:34:16,800 --> 00:34:19,000
well, because everyone
laughs at the older woman.

753
00:34:19,634 --> 00:34:21,700
no, not in this play. it's all serious.

754
00:34:23,833 --> 00:34:25,534
the act 1 curtain's good.

755
00:34:26,267 --> 00:34:27,999
it comes as a shock to her.

756
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:28,800
what does?

757
00:34:28,900 --> 00:34:30,967
that she's fallen in love with the boy.

758
00:34:32,200 --> 00:34:33,799
and it happens just when everything

759
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:36,034
seemed to her so dull and unpromising,

760
00:34:36,467 --> 00:34:38,134
as if her life was over.

761
00:34:38,400 --> 00:34:40,367
she finds the affair exhilarating.

762
00:34:41,300 --> 00:34:42,766
and everyone keeps telling her

763
00:34:42,967 --> 00:34:44,700
she looks 10 years younger.

764
00:34:45,134 --> 00:34:46,466
I trust she doesn't confess to the boy

765
00:34:46,667 --> 00:34:49,000
that she loves him. that's always fatal.

766
00:34:50,167 --> 00:34:51,466
does it sound like something for me?

767
00:34:51,667 --> 00:34:53,833
oh, don't be ridiculous, Julia.

768
00:34:55,100 --> 00:34:57,333
no, your public would
never stand for it.

769
00:34:57,634 --> 00:34:58,433
if such a woman asked me,

770
00:34:58,634 --> 00:34:59,899
I know what advice I'd give her.

771
00:35:00,100 --> 00:35:01,366
what? break it off at once.

772
00:35:01,567 --> 00:35:02,699
it will only end in tears.

773
00:35:02,900 --> 00:35:04,533
but, Charles, she can't do that.

774
00:35:04,734 --> 00:35:05,334
why ever not?

775
00:35:05,300 --> 00:35:07,266
because she's fallen in love with him,

776
00:35:07,467 --> 00:35:09,200
that's why. she's helpless.

777
00:35:09,467 --> 00:35:10,867
hmm.

778
00:35:12,700 --> 00:35:14,400
the character in the play.

779
00:35:24,467 --> 00:35:26,000
[door opens]

780
00:35:26,333 --> 00:35:27,900
dolly, old thing,

781
00:35:28,667 --> 00:35:29,933
how are you?

782
00:35:30,134 --> 00:35:32,134
I haven't seen you for ages.

783
00:35:34,134 --> 00:35:36,034
sit down and make yourself, uh,

784
00:35:38,700 --> 00:35:39,699
comfy.

785
00:35:39,900 --> 00:35:42,300
so, come to see that
the old firm's raking in

786
00:35:43,367 --> 00:35:43,967
the dividends for you?

787
00:35:44,134 --> 00:35:46,166
Michael, I'll come
straight to the point.

788
00:35:46,367 --> 00:35:47,732
you know I'm not one to gossip,

789
00:35:47,933 --> 00:35:50,066
but--but I'm
upset about Julia.

790
00:35:50,267 --> 00:35:50,867
[sighing]

791
00:35:50,900 --> 00:35:53,599
I think you ought to know that
people are beginning to talk.

792
00:35:53,800 --> 00:35:54,566
what the devil do you mean?

793
00:35:54,767 --> 00:35:56,734
well, it's absurd that at her age,

794
00:35:57,167 --> 00:35:58,999
she should make herself so conspicuous

795
00:35:59,200 --> 00:36:00,833
with a young boy.

796
00:36:01,400 --> 00:36:03,800
oh, you mean tom fennel?
don't be such a fool, dolly.

797
00:36:04,967 --> 00:36:05,599
I'm not a fool.

798
00:36:05,800 --> 00:36:07,699
when someone is as well-known as Julia

799
00:36:07,900 --> 00:36:10,300
and they're always seen with the
same man, naturally people talk.

800
00:36:11,200 --> 00:36:12,899
tom fennel is a very
good type of American.

801
00:36:13,100 --> 00:36:15,466
he's clean, honest and by
way of being a gentleman.

802
00:36:15,667 --> 00:36:17,833
he's boring, dull, common and a snob.

803
00:36:19,100 --> 00:36:21,300
he's just using Julia.
